posts.name: Joseph Farkas
posts.cooked:
Hi all. After updating and refactoring some code to 2022 WPILIB, our robot refused to run the code (stating “No Robot Code” in the driver station), and starting spewing errors into the console, including the one mentioned in the title and some CTR errors (check the image attached). After attempting to debug for an hour or 2 (Rio updated, all CTRE devices updated, experimentation with code), I was able to narrow down the issue to a few possible culprits. The main one is the CTRE devices being initialized too early. In previous years, they were initialized in the .cpp file, outside of any method, so that is how I did it this year. However, I suspect CTRE has changed some things in their library that may require initialization inside an init method (I will try this at the next meeting, but it is in a few days and my time with the robot will be limited as it will soon be disassembled, so I would like to gather a few possible ideas of things to try and see if this is happening to anyone else). However, this may not be the full extent of the problem. Using the Phoenix Tuner and a tether, I was able to get the CTRE devices to show up and the “Code not found” error disappears. But upon running the code, nothing happens (the first line is a printf() and nothing is printed). The next possible idea I came up with is a problem in the AHRS library provided by KauaiLabs (yes, I did update to the 2022 version), as it does call the GetFPGATimestamp method. We also thought of an issue with the RoboRio OS, as the FPGA method interacts directly with the RoboRio. Is anyone else having these issues? Thanks!

Image from iOS (1)|666x500

posts.name: Joseph Farkas
posts.cooked: The kinematics constructor takes dereferenced SwerveModule pointers, which are defined as nullptr at compilation time, so won’t that be an issue?

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked: Whoops, you’re right, reading too quickly.

posts.name: Joseph Farkas
posts.cooked: I do that all the time. Thanks again for your help; I’ll test ASAP.

posts.name: Joseph Farkas
posts.cooked: Sorry, I forgot to reply. Your fix worked splendidly, and I now am initializing anything that needs access to the RoboRIO in Robot::Robot(). Thanks for the help!
